How well do you know your body?⁣
⠀⁣
Around every areola are little bumps called Montgomery Glands⠀⁣
⠀⁣
They secrete a substance that helps protect your nipples and actually helps attract newborns to the breast because the scent is similar to amniotic fluid!⠀⁣
⠀⁣
The number of these glands vary but they are definitely normal and you may even notice them enlarging during pregnancy ⠀⁣
⠀⁣
During pregnancy, the areola darkens because there is an increase in melanin deposits. Melanin is what gives skin its pigment ⠀⁣
⠀⁣
It’s common for the areola to enlarge as well. You’ll likely also notice veins across your chest becoming more prominent ⠀⁣
⠀⁣
All normal changes! And all changes an IBCLC will take note of during a consultation ⠀⁣
⁣
Your nipple also has an average of 9 pores for milk to come out of! Not just one. ⁣
⁣
In fact, there’s a range of 4-18 openings⁣
⠀⁣
This can surprise a lot of people the very first time they see this happening whether they are hand expressing or using a pump⁣
⠀⁣
It’s much more noticeable after your body starts producing more milk ⠀⁣
⠀⁣
If you didn’t know this before, I am so happy you found this information! ⁣
⁣

But this doesn’t work for everyone 

Whatever your reason for weaning, a slow and gentle process is ideal for both of you (if you have that option) ⁣
⁣

⁣
♥️ You can eliminate a feeding - depending on the age of your child it may need to be replaced with formula or donor milk ⁣
⁣
♥️ You can set boundaries around feeding times if you’re nursing a toddler ⁣

♥️ You can add other comforting techniques into nap time/overnight routines ⁣

This is VERY popular weaning advice easily found online⁣
⁣
And while it can work for some people, here’s why it’s not for everyone ⁣
⁣
Don’t refuse: if you have a toddler who is always wanting to nurse (they’re an extra limb it feels like they’re nursing so much) never refusing isn’t going to help you wean. ⁣
⁣
And if you have that child and are trying to implement weaning strategies, chances are you’re already feeling touched out ⁣
⁣
Don’t offer: what if you have a 2,2.5,3 year old and if you didn’t offer they’d just happily go about their day and not nurse? While it might be helping you get to your goals you’ll have to remove milk at some point to manage any discomfort or fullness (though it could take a while) and to prevent engorgement and inflammation leading to narrowing ducts⁣
⁣
This is where an IBCLC (🙋🏻‍♀️) can help you. ⁣
I can provide you realistic strategies and tips to gently begin the weaning process with your toddler (12+months) beyond ‘don’t offer, don’t refuse’⁣

Would you believe me if I said you were the expert of your baby? No one knows your baby better than you⁣!⁣
⁣⁣
When you feel like something is wrong, chances are you’re right. I encourage you to always seek support when you feel something is wrong⁣⁣
⁣⁣
I would also suggest connecting with a lactation consultant if you’re experiencing any of these signs⁣⁣
⁣⁣
🚩 Pain or damage of any kind from nursing or pumping ⁣⁣
🚩 Hearing a clicking or smacking sound when your baby is feeding ⁣
🚩 If you’re using a nipple shield ⁣
🚩 If baby is coughing or choking while feeding ⁣⁣
🚩 If your nipples are coming out in a different shape, especially if there’s pain associated with it ⁣⁣
🚩 Pinching feelings ⁣⁣
⭐️ Anytime something doesn’t feel right. This includes a previous suggestion from a different lactation consultant!⁣
⁣⁣
If it doesn’t sit right with you, find someone who will listen and help you solve the problem. You and your baby deserve that ⁣

🦷 Biting sucks but it doesn’t mean you have to wean or transition to bottles

🤷🏻‍♀️ So what can you do? 

🔹As hard as it is, try not to yell as it could startle and scare and *possibly* lead to a nursing strike 

🔹 Silicone teething toys - I loved keeping 1 in the fridge to offer baby before breastfeeding 

🔹 Gum massage

🔹 Go back to the latch basics because a baby can’t bite if they’re actually latched (they actually need to move their tongue out of the way for the bite to happen) 

🔹 Watch them during a feeding and unlatch if you see them starting to possibly bite 

🔹If your baby has not started solids, frozen breastmilk in a feeding teether does wonders to help soothe their sore gums

Your baby’s latch can actually affect your supply!⁣
⁣⁣
Here’s how: ⁣
⁣⁣
For example, if your baby has a shallow latch, they may have a hard time removing milk beyond the initial let down ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
If milk isn’t adequately removed, it can begin to slow down production ⁣⁣
⁣
And you’ll produce less milk ⁣
⁣
This is why IBCLCs will say “protect your supply” when you’re waiting for an appointment or working through a nursing challenge ⁣
⁣
This means using pumping (electric or manual depending on your unique situation and circumstances) and/or hand expression to remove milk when/if your baby is unable to ⁣
⁣
And getting support for the root cause of baby’s inability to effectively drink from the breast ⁣
⁣

Busy babies - babies learning to crawl, stand, cruise, climb stairs and walk 

These babies often do a lot of “drive by” nursing where it’s a quick few minutes and then they’re on their way

Often, this means more night time nursing which is completely expected and normal for this age group 

Rather than always waiting for their cue or using a schedule, try offering proactively - you know it’s been a while since their last feed, they’ve been moving about and busy, give them the chance to nurse or bottle feed 

If you’re not with them during the day, chat with their care giver about how they’re eating during the day and see if the caregiver notices anything like this - shorter feeds or longer stretches between feeds especially if you’re noticing things are a bit different once you’re home with them

Hand expression is a valuable skill that is under taught and under utilized ⠀
⠀
👋🏼Hand expression is a manual method of milk expression that should not hurt you or cause any bruising ⠀
⠀
👌🏾Hand expression is a great tool to use if you find yourself without a pump BUT it’s also valuable to learn before your baby arrives to use in the first few days after birth to express colostrum and support the transition of your milk
⠀
👍🏿Hand expression is cost effective because it doesn’t require any equipment ⠀
⠀
👏🏻Hand expression can be used without electricity or batteries 
⠀
🤟🏼Hand expression can be used if you are separated from your baby after birth (or separated from your pump!) 
⠀
🤙🏽Hand expression is also the method used to collect colostrum BEFORE your baby is born

Search ‘hand expression’ on my blog for more but the basic steps are 

1️⃣ Gently massage with clean hands 
2️⃣ Make a C shape, placing your fingers 1-2 inches from the nipple 
3️⃣ Press back (inwards towards your ribs/chest wall) 
4️⃣ Compress, gently bringing your fingers together (not dragging across your skin)
5️⃣ Release - perform this again, making your way around the tissue ⠀

You’re not failing if you’re not filling up these collection bottles when you pump 

Yes, some people can but average milk production is about an ounce an hour which is 24oz in 24 hours 

The volume you pump will fluctuate throughout the day as well as day to day and depends on many factors 

⏺ If you’re also nursing 
⏺ Time in between pump sessions
⏺ The fit of your flange 
⏺ The shape of the flange
⏺ If you’re using a pumping bra or holding the flanges on yourself 
⏺ Stress and anxiety levels 
⏺ And more! 

So if you feel like you’re not producing enough, know the goal isn’t to be filling these bottles but to feed your baby in a way that feels good for you 

And if that means increasing your supply, work with an IBCLC 🙋🏻‍♀️

While it might make sense that leaving a breast fuller for longer will “build up” the milk this is not actually what happens long term 

To naturally support your milk production: 
⠀
✅ Focus on an effective latch. One that’s comfortable for both of you and your baby is able to drink (ask for help if you’re struggling with that)⠀
⠀
✅ Feed your baby on demand when they display early hunger cues ⠀
⠀
✅ Don’t limit their time spent at the breast meaning don’t follow the “15 mins a side”
⠀
✅ Offer the other side after they finish the first ⠀
⠀
Doing this all the time right from the start will naturally support your milk regulation. As your baby grows and slowly begins to sleep for longer periods of time, your body will gradually begin to slow down milk production to what matches the milk removal⠀

If you’re struggling with this, reach out to an IBCLC🙋🏻‍♀️ for personalized support

Breastfeeding with large breasts can be done but it can feel tricky at first. Especially because it can be hard to see your nipple and how your baby is latched ⁣
⁣
Or you can feel like your breast is too heavy for them so you find yourself holding or supporting it so your baby stays latched⁣
⁣
Adding some gentle lift and support from underneath can help make latching easier! ⁣
⁣
You can make a sling using a scarf by folding it up on itself lengthwise and then tying the ends together ⁣
⁣
Bonus tips:⁣
⁣
❇️ Have patience. It may be challenging at first and may require you to try and modify a few different positions before you’re feeling comfortable ⁣
⁣
❇️ Side lying position can be a great option because your breast is supported by the bed/couch ⁣
⁣
❇️ Roll up a swaddle blanket or a small towel and place it underneath the breast to provide some additional support and lift the breast ⁣
⁣

Do you know your flange size? Chances are it’s smaller than what came with your pump 

When I was pumping with my first I was using a 24mm flange when I really needed a 15mm

You may even need a different shaped flange or material like silicone instead of hard plastic 

Every BODY is different 

Pumping with a flange that’s too large can and often does work but overtime, you may start to see a change in your production 

You may start to experience swelling or inflammation leading to ‘clogs’

You may end up with pinching or damage to your areola or nipple especially as your nipple size changes in the weeks after birth 

New flanges can be purchased and so can inserts to help you create the best fit 

Did someone help you figure out your flange size?

A previously loved pump may not always be the best option

It can be difficult to determine just how frequently the pump was used. While you can replace just about all of the physical parts, the motor may or may not be in great shape

It’s also important to consider whether it is a closed system or not as moisture could have made its way into the motor if it’s not. 

If it turns out you need to pump often and you’re using a second hand pump that was used frequently, the motor may not be up to the task. This could affect how efficient it is at removing milk which could begin to affect milk supply

Think about the length of your mat leave if you have one, what your goals for feeding your baby are and meet with an IBCLC prenatally to chat all things pumping!

So first, just because I see these often in my practice does not mean they’re the only causes 

A full health history and feeding evaluation should be completed by an IBCLC if you’re having concerns over your supply 

1. No stimulation in the 24 hrs after birth whether this is nursing or hand expression 
2. Spacing out or scheduling feedings as a means to space out feedings
3. Cutting out night feeds (nursing or pumping) too early. Before 12 months or before your baby is naturally sleeping longer stretches and going without a feeding on their own 

The reason these affect supply is because they impact how often milk is being removed and if this happens in the first few weeks to months after birth, it can begin to impact supply

Less removals and less stimulation means your body gets the signals that less milk is needed over time so production slows down and it’s seen and described as a drop in supply 

I have seen spacing out feedings and trying to cut out night feeds too early begin to impact weight gain as well which is why I’m always working to get to the root of what’s going on to help my clients reach their feedings goals

Colostrum is your baby’s first milk

This is such a common worry I hear so you’re not alone if you too are worried about this⁣
⁣
When nursing, we can’t see how much milk our baby is consuming so it’s easy to wonder if they are getting enough milk⁣⁣
⁣
I was told my firstborn needed to be supplemented with formula but I didn’t really know the details ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
When I look back at his records (my midwives provided me copies of everything) he had normal weight gain (back to birth weight by 10 days) and yellow stools by day 5⁣⁣
⁣⁣
My first lactation appointment should have gone much differently but that’s a story for another day ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
So how can you tell if your baby is getting enough? ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
1️⃣ When you’re nursing your baby, keep your eyes on your baby. If you are seeing their drop low and taking a pause after sucking, your baby is swallowing milk⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Swallows means they are drinking ✅⁣⁣
⁣⁣
2️⃣ Another thing to keeps your eyes on is your baby’s diapers. If your baby is drinking enough milk, you’ll be changing lots of wet and poopy diapers⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Typically we want to see 1 wet and 1 poopy diaper for each day of life for the first week⁣⁣
⁣⁣
3️⃣ Weight gain is another key sign your little one is drinking lots of milk (weight loss should stop by day 5 and their growth should follow a curve on the WHO charts)

Follow your baby’s lead. I like to suggest offering the other side every time but not to stress about it if your baby doesn’t accept it⠀⁣
⠀⁣
Some babies will feed from both sides and some are content with just one at a time. Sometimes the same baby will nurse from both at one feeding and then just one at another.⁣
⠀⁣
There are times when it’s really important to always offer both:⁣
⁣
⏺ After birth when you’re establishing your production (more below) ⁣
⏺ If your baby is not back to birth weight or struggling with weight gain⁣
⏺ If you’re trying to increase your milk production ⁣
⏺ If your baby is having any challenges nursing/ removing milk⁣
⠀⁣
Right after birth, your body is waiting to be told how many babies need to be fed. The more often a baby is at the breast and milk is effectively removed, the more milk will be made⠀⁣
 ⠀⁣
If you’re not telling both breasts to make milk each feed, your body will adjust and slow down the speed milk is made. This *could* mean you begin to produce less than your baby needs or it *could* mean your body reduces to exactly what your baby needs. Everyone is different. ⁣
⠀⁣
My firstborn alway fed on both sides each nursing session. My second? He was almost always one at time with a break in between.⁣
⠀⁣
AND if you have just one breast - the body is often quite able to produce a full supply to breastfeed a baby. It depends on your unique history. In these situations I suggest working with an IBCLC prior to your baby’s arrival to discuss expectations and create a plan.⁣
⁣
What about your baby? Are they one at a time? Or both? ⁣

It can be exhausting, stressful and saddening always wondering if your baby is getting enough milk⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Supply concerns are consistently reported in the research when it comes to reasons for stopping breastfeeding⁣⁣
⁣⁣
And it’s a common concern I see when people reach out to work with me ⁣
⁣⁣
I get it⁣⁣
⁣⁣
I was there myself for several weeks with my firstborn ⁣
⁣
I see these 3 often but as the images say, they’re not the only reasons⁣
⁣
1️⃣ Little or no stimulation in the first 24 hours after birth can create challenges because this is a key period of time to begin to tell your body that your baby needs milk ⁣
⁣
2️⃣ Scheduling or spacing out feedings (or pumping sessions) can begin to slow down your milk production because it tells your body that your baby needs less milk so your body makes less ⁣
⁣
3️⃣ Trying to drop night feeds too early does the same as number 2, tells your body your baby needs less milk since milk is not being removed ⁣
⁣
Also, this is the period of time when your milk making hormone, prolactin, is highest which helps to continue to drive supply during the day⁣
⁣
And no, there’s no scientific evidence that says once your baby is ‘X’ lbs/kgs that they no longer need to eat at night ⁣
⁣
These may seems like very small things but over a period of time (which is different for everyone) your body WILL get the signals that say ‘I don’t need to make milk as quickly anymore’ and supply drops ⁣
⁣
If you want to better understand how your milk production works and what you can do to maximize it (without cookies and teas) I have a fr.ee webinar available called Make More Milk ⁣

Use Reverse Pressure Softening!

⠀⁣

It can be exhausting and upsetting always wondering if your baby is getting enough milk⁣⁣⁣
⁣
Supply concerns are consistently reported in the research when it comes to reasons for stopping breastfeeding⁣⁣⁣
⁣
And it’s a common concern I see when people reach out to work with me⁣
⁣
I get it⁣⁣. I was there myself for several weeks with my firstborn ⁣
⁣
I see these 3 often but as the images say, they’re not the only reasons⁣ ⁣
⁣
1️⃣ An ineffective latch. Not necessarily a ‘bad latch’ but a latch where baby isn’t quite able to drink milk well. This affects how well milk is removed⁣
⁣
2️⃣ Scheduling or spacing out feedings (or pumping sessions) can begin to slow down your milk production because it tells your body that your baby needs less milk so your body makes less⁣
⁣
3️⃣ Trying to drop night feeds too early does the same as number 2, tells your body your baby needs less milk since milk is not being removed. Also, this is the period of time when your milk making hormone, prolactin, is highest which helps to continue to drive supply during the day⁣⁣
⁣
And no, there’s no scientific evidence that says once your baby is ‘X’ lbs/kgs that they no longer need to eat at night⁣
⁣
These may seems like very small things but over a period of time (which is different for everyone) your body WILL get the signals that say ‘I don’t need to make milk as quickly anymore’ and supply drops⁣
⁣

⁣
Clogs/plugged ducts feel like little firm bumps, lumps or marbles in the breast (sometimes they feel larger) ⁣
⁣
Generally this feeling makes you want to massage them out but the thing is, your breast tissue is not muscle ⁣
⁣
You can’t massage it with the same force you’d massage your leg or foot ⁣
⁣
This can actually damage the delicate tissues and then inflammation happens and your plugged ducts can quickly escalate to mastitis ⁣
⁣
Mastitis feels more like your breast is bruised and tender (even if it didn’t happen from aggressive massaging) ⁣
⁣
And if you want to treat either of these, this is what you have to keep in mind ⁣
⁣
➡️ Focus on reducing the inflammation and be gentle with your body ⁣
⁣
✅ Breastfeed (nurse or pump) as usual⁣
⁣
You don’t want to try and keep the breast as empty as possible just keep your routine ⁣
⁣
Excess pumping can increase inflammation further making matters worse and potentially lead to an overproduction depending on how quickly your body responds which is an entirely new challenge to manage⁣
⁣
✅ Use gentle lymphatic massage to move the fluid out ⁣
⁣
There a few techniques but Maya Bolman, IBCLC developed a technique called ‘breast gymnastics’ which can be very helpful for inflammatory conditions like mastitis⁣
⁣
Think of it like a sprained ankle 👉🏻 Treat it gently and with care⁣

While it might be nice to have, it’s not a necessity for everyone

Even if you’re returning to work quickly, you still don’t need a huge stash⁣

You need about 1-1.5oz (30-45mL) for every hour you’re away from your baby 

So an 8 hour day is 8-12oz. Saving 2-3 *work days* with of milk is 16-36oz 

So you don’t actually need 50+ oz in your freezer 
⁣
Could there be exceptions and special circumstances, sure. 

Will someone reading this have had a huge stash, gotten sick and relied on that frozen milk? Yes 

But generally speaking, if you’re preparing for back to work, you can spend a couple weeks collecting your first 16-36oz and from there, the pumping you do away from baby supplies the milk for the next day

Your milk making hormone prolactin increases overnight ⁣
